author: Richard Black
text:
No one has posted a negative comment yet so I guess ill be that guy.
India must be backwards and primitive to think that Biomass generators are renewable but nuclear is not. 
small scale hydro power only? what fools... Dams only get more energy efficient when they get larger.
using arable farmland for solar farm instillation is a really inhumane decision. you flipped a coin between feeding your people and giving them electricity.



Nuclear power is the closest thing this world has to a perfect energy source. it only has two flaws which can easily be fixed:
1. risk of meltdown. a catastrophic failure only happens at old, outdated, poorly maintained, or improperly expanded power facilities.
if innovation and engineering can make solar and wind cheap; then it can make Nuclear safe.
2. disposal of nuclear waste. solid nuclear waste should be stable at an average underground facility, as long as the area is not prone to earthquakes, floods or erosion.
in most countries the perfect area would be at the bottom or large open pit mines. Nuclear waste inside a 3" thick lead cylinder, inside a steel cylinder coated in epoxy, bundled together at the bottom of the hole (500 feet below the surface) surround the containers in concrete, insert tungsten plaques baring the radioactive symbol, and fill in the hole with the mined out dirt.

author: Robert Schuster
text: I just don't like seeing arable land taken up by solar panels.  I like the rooftops and canal covers.  One thing not mentioned and maybe because they don't consider it renewable is LFTR technology.  I know India is working on it and I hope they get some plants into production soon for proof of concept so that other countries will follow their lead.

reply.author: Stephen Kelly
reply.text: Robert Schuster Well those lands are really used so it's better to do it that way because most homes in India aren't strong enough to house an array of solar panels.

reply.author: Jay Patel
reply.text: soon solar panel will be in most house because solar panel is getting cheap day by day and also indian government is giving subsidies in solar panel.

reply.author: gcKukie
reply.text: Where i live people grow ginseng under large nets, it would make total sense to build a solar farm that blocks the same amount of light as the netting for that situation, but i hear where your coming from, farmland is more important than people in the cities want to believe.

reply.author: Robert Schuster
reply.text: Until all the roof tops are covered with solar panels, It just seems self defeating to make places where greenery can grow barren.  After all, plants do more to take carbon out of the air than anything else. If it's not a good area for food crops, at least trees or grass could grow there. The only places I can justify putting solar farms is out in an already barren area.
